1
00:00:01,272 --> 00:00:03,158
(bright music)

2
00:00:03,158 --> 00:00:05,991
(birds chirping)

3
00:00:12,615 --> 00:00:15,615
(pecans clattering)

4
00:01:09,063 --> 00:01:11,813
(birds chirping)

5
00:01:14,877 --> 00:01:16,780
- Enable us today, O' Lord,

6
00:01:16,780 --> 00:01:20,123
to reflect on the life of
our beloved Emma Barnsdow.

7
00:01:21,030 --> 00:01:24,310
May her tradition of
love and charity live on

8
00:01:24,310 --> 00:01:27,220
in the hearts of her
two beautiful daughters,

9
00:01:27,220 --> 00:01:30,410
Sarah, who has joined
us from Atlanta today,

10
00:01:30,410 --> 00:01:32,660
and our own dear Wanda.

11
00:01:32,660 --> 00:01:34,960
Bless and keep them both.

12
00:01:34,960 --> 00:01:35,793
Amen.

13
00:01:35,793 --> 00:01:36,626
- [People] Amen.

14
00:01:39,406 --> 00:01:40,750
- Thank you, Reverend.

15
00:01:40,750 --> 00:01:42,231
- Reverend.

16
00:01:42,231 --> 00:01:44,503
(people conversing softly)

17
00:01:44,503 --> 00:01:46,590
- Darling, if there's anything I can do.

18
00:01:46,590 --> 00:01:48,507
- Thank you, Reverend.
(Ruby cooing)

19
00:01:48,507 --> 00:01:50,341
(people conversing in distance)

20
00:01:50,341 --> 00:01:52,650
(Sarah sighs)

21
00:01:52,650 --> 00:01:54,400
Thank you for coming.

22
00:01:56,220 --> 00:01:57,877
- It was very nice, Wanda.

23
00:01:59,030 --> 00:01:59,863
- What?

24
00:02:00,760 --> 00:02:01,643
- The ceremony.

25
00:02:02,490 --> 00:02:03,893
Mother would've been very proud.

26
00:02:07,815 --> 00:02:09,948
- Hi, Gina.
- Hi, Aunt Wanda.

27
00:02:09,948 --> 00:02:11,157
- Edmond.

28
00:02:11,157 --> 00:02:12,373
- You're not staying?

29
00:02:13,450 --> 00:02:15,300
Everybody's coming over to the house.

30
00:02:16,170 --> 00:02:17,003
- Well, I'd love to,

31
00:02:17,003 --> 00:02:18,680
but I need to get back to Atlanta.

32
00:02:18,680 --> 00:02:20,020
- Jerry's very busy.

33
00:02:20,020 --> 00:02:21,640
Gina and I are gonna
take him to the airport,

34
00:02:21,640 --> 00:02:22,670
and then we'll be back.

35
00:02:22,670 --> 00:02:25,040
I hope we don't miss too much.

36
00:02:25,040 --> 00:02:26,970
- No, anytime is fine.

37
00:02:32,460 --> 00:02:33,460
- [Sarah] Bye, dear.

38
00:02:34,644 --> 00:02:37,095
(somber music)

39
00:02:37,095 --> 00:02:40,012
(insects chirping)

40
00:02:41,272 --> 00:02:43,939
(mellow music)

41
00:02:45,432 --> 00:02:46,773
- Hey, there, baby, did you know

42
00:02:46,773 --> 00:02:47,897
that when I was a little girl,

43
00:02:47,897 --> 00:02:51,040
your grandma had a magic
yellow rain bucket,

44
00:02:51,040 --> 00:02:52,050
and she used to use it whenever

45
00:02:52,050 --> 00:02:54,250
she wanted to make it stop raining.

46
00:02:54,250 --> 00:02:56,650
All she had to do was just set it outside,

47
00:02:56,650 --> 00:02:57,960
and before you knew it,

48
00:02:57,960 --> 00:02:59,783
we could go back out and play again.

49
00:02:59,783 --> 00:03:00,616
Yes.

50
00:03:01,460 --> 00:03:03,010
Just like this one.

51
00:03:03,010 --> 00:03:05,324
- Almost as pretty as her mama.

52
00:03:05,324 --> 00:03:06,157
You okay, honey?

53
00:03:06,157 --> 00:03:08,290
- Yes.
- You need anything?

54
00:03:08,290 --> 00:03:09,920
- No, but thanks.
(Rudy cooing)

55
00:03:09,920 --> 00:03:11,550
- I'll put Ruby to bed.

56
00:03:11,550 --> 00:03:12,714
Come on.

57
00:03:12,714 --> 00:03:14,047
- Come on, baby.

58
00:03:23,433 --> 00:03:26,433
(crickets chirping)

59
00:03:39,470 --> 00:03:41,080
- Gina, take off the headset.

60
00:03:41,080 --> 00:03:42,620
It won't hurt you to be sociable.

61
00:03:42,620 --> 00:03:43,486
Gina!

62
00:03:43,486 --> 00:03:44,760
(heavy metal music plays in headphone)

63
00:03:44,760 --> 00:03:45,593
Thank you.

64
00:03:52,316 --> 00:03:53,598
(soft knocking on door)

65
00:03:53,598 --> 00:03:54,431
Wanda!

66
00:03:56,849 --> 00:03:57,682
You up?

67
00:03:59,055 --> 00:04:00,805
Hi, sorry we're late.

68
00:04:02,797 --> 00:04:04,830
Jerry's flight was delayed.

69
00:04:04,830 --> 00:04:05,970
Gina.

70
00:04:05,970 --> 00:04:07,790
- Gina, sweetheart, I
didn't see you out there.

71
00:04:07,790 --> 00:04:09,640
How you doing, sweetheart?

72
00:04:09,640 --> 00:04:10,473
Come on in.

73
00:04:10,473 --> 00:04:12,681
Why don't you go on inside.

74
00:04:15,220 --> 00:04:18,510
- Wanda, I wanted you to
know how much I appreciate

75
00:04:18,510 --> 00:04:20,133
everything you did for mama,

76
00:04:20,969 --> 00:04:22,719
and I'm sorry I didn't come sooner.

77
00:04:23,680 --> 00:04:25,280
- I'm surprised you came at all.

78
00:04:29,069 --> 00:04:31,223
- That was quite a turn out you had.

79
00:04:32,107 --> 00:04:32,940
I'm sorry.

80
00:04:34,437 --> 00:04:37,240
Business has been so hectic
these past few years.

81
00:04:37,240 --> 00:04:39,033
I hope you know it wasn't personal.

82
00:04:40,059 --> 00:04:41,813
I hardly see Jerry anymore.

83
00:04:44,990 --> 00:04:46,174
How you holding up, Wanda?

84
00:04:46,174 --> 00:04:47,100
(Wanda sighs in frustration)

85
00:04:47,100 --> 00:04:48,403
- Save it Sarah.

86
00:04:51,060 --> 00:04:52,940
- I was thinking of asking
you to visit up in Atlanta,

87
00:04:52,940 --> 00:04:55,260
but I guess that's out of the question.

88
00:04:55,260 --> 00:04:57,360
- You can stay in the back room.

89
00:04:57,360 --> 00:04:58,670
Eddie had it fixed for mama

90
00:04:58,670 --> 00:05:00,960
when we moved her from the nursing home.

91
00:05:00,960 --> 00:05:01,920
- Oh, that's real nice,

92
00:05:01,920 --> 00:05:03,310
but I think we'll get a hotel room.

93
00:05:03,310 --> 00:05:05,060
- Well, there's no point in
that because Mr. Hampton's

94
00:05:05,060 --> 00:05:07,960
coming at eight o'clock tomorrow
morning to read the will.

95
00:05:09,290 --> 00:05:11,833
- Hi, Eddie I hope we didn't wake you.

96
00:05:11,833 --> 00:05:13,960
- No. (coughs)

97
00:05:13,960 --> 00:05:16,490
No, we're glad you're here.

98
00:05:16,490 --> 00:05:18,351
Can I help you with your bags?

99
00:05:18,351 --> 00:05:20,023
- They're in the car.

100
00:05:20,023 --> 00:05:20,856
- We're gonna be having breakfast

101
00:05:20,856 --> 00:05:22,903
before Mr. Hampton gets
here in the morning.

102
00:05:28,500 --> 00:05:30,573
Gina can sleep on the pull out sofa.

103
00:05:33,674 --> 00:05:35,170
You'll wanna keep the fan on,

104
00:05:35,170 --> 00:05:36,690
so the room doesn't get too hot.

105
00:05:36,690 --> 00:05:37,740
When you use the bathroom,

106
00:05:37,740 --> 00:05:40,490
just jiggle the handle on
the back of the toilet, okay?

107
00:05:45,686 --> 00:05:46,960
(birds chirping)

108
00:05:46,960 --> 00:05:50,660
- I'd also like Wanda to
have my China tableware,

109
00:05:50,660 --> 00:05:55,660
my 19-inch Magnavox television
set, shoes, clothing,

110
00:05:55,660 --> 00:05:57,980
and all remaining
belongings not so designated

111
00:05:57,980 --> 00:06:02,514
in above mentioned exhibits
one and two respectively.

112
00:06:02,514 --> 00:06:03,810
(attorney coughs)

113
00:06:03,810 --> 00:06:04,643
Moving on.

114
00:06:05,640 --> 00:06:08,573
Finally, to my daughter Sarah,

115
00:06:10,270 --> 00:06:13,563
I bequeath my leather reclining chair.

116
00:06:16,483 --> 00:06:18,500
- What that's it?

117
00:06:18,500 --> 00:06:20,186
I get the strata lounger lounger,

118
00:06:20,186 --> 00:06:23,780
and she gets everything else?

119
00:06:23,780 --> 00:06:26,430
- Maybe mama didn't think
you needed anything, Sarah.

120
00:06:31,570 --> 00:06:32,573
- What that's it?

121
00:06:34,395 --> 00:06:35,860
- I'm afraid so.

122
00:06:35,860 --> 00:06:37,200
- Well, what about the property?

123
00:06:37,200 --> 00:06:39,660
- That's right the pecan grove.

124
00:06:39,660 --> 00:06:41,023
Mama didn't say anything?

125
00:06:42,790 --> 00:06:46,950
- I wasn't aware of any pecan groves.

126
00:06:46,950 --> 00:06:48,310
You see it's unfortunate,

127
00:06:48,310 --> 00:06:50,040
but my partner Mr. Lattimore,

128
00:06:50,040 --> 00:06:53,230
who prepared this for your mother,

129
00:06:53,230 --> 00:06:54,727
he died several years ago.

130
00:06:54,727 --> 00:06:57,180
- It's about a hundred
acres up off Highway Seven.

131
00:06:57,180 --> 00:06:58,824
Surely, that's worth something.

132
00:06:58,824 --> 00:07:01,230
- Well, Benjamin he was real thorough.

133
00:07:01,230 --> 00:07:04,000
I just can't imagine
how it slipped through.

134
00:07:04,000 --> 00:07:04,833
- Have you been out there?

135
00:07:04,833 --> 00:07:06,870
I mean do you know what
kind of condition it's in?

136
00:07:06,870 --> 00:07:09,220
- The only time I saw it
was when I was driving by.

137
00:07:09,220 --> 00:07:10,980
Mama used to go out there
once in a while though

138
00:07:10,980 --> 00:07:12,600
until she got six.

139
00:07:12,600 --> 00:07:14,210
- (sighs) So what happens now?

140
00:07:14,210 --> 00:07:16,880
I mean how long can this take in probate?

141
00:07:16,880 --> 00:07:17,713
- Oh, well,

142
00:07:19,520 --> 00:07:21,443
I know Judge McNamara.

143
00:07:22,620 --> 00:07:25,350
I suppose I could speed it through.

144
00:07:25,350 --> 00:07:27,280
Of course, you know by default,

145
00:07:27,280 --> 00:07:29,863
you both would be named as beneficiaries.

146
00:07:30,800 --> 00:07:33,980
- So we split it equally 50/50?

147
00:07:35,951 --> 00:07:38,063
(gentle music)

148
00:07:38,063 --> 00:07:40,896
(birds chirping)

149
00:08:00,500 --> 00:08:01,860
- Mom, when are we going home?

150
00:08:01,860 --> 00:08:03,053
This place sucks.

151
00:08:07,458 --> 00:08:10,611
- Well, it is certainly not
the way mother described it.

152
00:08:10,611 --> 00:08:11,444
- [Wanda] Well, of course not.

153
00:08:11,444 --> 00:08:13,658
Nobody took care of it after daddy died.

154
00:08:13,658 --> 00:08:16,325
(gentle music)

155
00:08:27,202 --> 00:08:29,220
- To make things really exciting,

156
00:08:29,220 --> 00:08:30,840
here's an old paint can.

157
00:08:30,840 --> 00:08:33,963
Perhaps left behind by
some ancient civilization.

158
00:08:35,210 --> 00:08:38,620
Maybe there's a slug we
can put on mom's head.

159
00:08:38,620 --> 00:08:40,213
- Oh, look.

160
00:08:40,213 --> 00:08:42,760
Look that must be the
old tractor daddy had.

161
00:08:42,760 --> 00:08:44,860
Oh, he used to talk
about this all the time.

162
00:08:44,860 --> 00:08:45,693
- Uh-huh.

163
00:08:56,470 --> 00:08:57,363
- Mom.

164
00:08:58,985 --> 00:09:00,329
Mom.

165
00:09:00,329 --> 00:09:01,250
Mom.

166
00:09:01,250 --> 00:09:03,305
- Gina.
- There's a pathway.

167
00:09:03,305 --> 00:09:04,138
- Yeah.

168
00:09:05,902 --> 00:09:08,190
(Sarah sighs)

169
00:09:08,190 --> 00:09:09,300
Oh, don't go.

170
00:09:09,300 --> 00:09:11,560
Gina, you'll wreck your outfit.

171
00:09:11,560 --> 00:09:13,830
- The grove suddenly came alive.

172
00:09:13,830 --> 00:09:17,201
A secret passage leading
deep into the nether regions.

173
00:09:17,201 --> 00:09:21,385
- [Sarah] Gina wait up.

174
00:09:21,385 --> 00:09:22,776
Gina.

175
00:09:22,776 --> 00:09:24,477
(cat mews)
- Oh, look.

176
00:09:24,477 --> 00:09:25,883
It's a baby panther.

177
00:09:27,090 --> 00:09:27,923
Did you lose your mother?

178
00:09:27,923 --> 00:09:29,580
- [Sarah] Gina, don't touch that cat.

179
00:09:30,850 --> 00:09:31,683
What the?

180
00:09:31,683 --> 00:09:35,438
- Oh, it's daddy's old pecan shack.

181
00:09:35,438 --> 00:09:37,583
- I think someone's living in there.

182
00:09:37,583 --> 00:09:39,080
(door creaks)

183
00:09:39,080 --> 00:09:39,913
- Jasper.

184
00:09:41,423 --> 00:09:44,630
William, come on babies it's super time.

185
00:09:44,630 --> 00:09:47,480
Mama done made some okra and corn bread.

186
00:09:47,480 --> 00:09:48,313
Skeeter.

187
00:09:49,270 --> 00:09:51,710
Edda Mae, y'all come on now.

188
00:09:51,710 --> 00:09:52,543
- Oh, my gosh.

189
00:09:53,706 --> 00:09:55,513
(leaves rustling)

190
00:09:55,513 --> 00:09:58,883
(birds chirping)

191
00:09:58,883 --> 00:10:00,035
- Who in there?

192
00:10:00,035 --> 00:10:01,070
(gun firing)
(women gasping)

193
00:10:01,070 --> 00:10:02,477
Y'all get off this land, you hear?

194
00:10:02,477 --> 00:10:04,930
This here is private property!

195
00:10:04,930 --> 00:10:06,817
No trespassing!

196
00:10:06,817 --> 00:10:08,010
(birds chirping)

197
00:10:08,010 --> 00:10:09,380
(insects chittering)

198
00:10:09,380 --> 00:10:10,980
I'm warning you.

199
00:10:10,980 --> 00:10:12,380
- Gina don't.
- Who's that?

200
00:10:13,390 --> 00:10:14,223
Who is that?

201
00:10:16,187 --> 00:10:17,780
- (stammering) I'm.

202
00:10:17,780 --> 00:10:20,563
- Field Pea is that you?

203
00:10:21,890 --> 00:10:24,230
Praise the Lord that is you.

204
00:10:24,230 --> 00:10:27,450
You done come all the way
from Clearwater to see me.

205
00:10:27,450 --> 00:10:28,657
- [Sarah] Gina.

206
00:10:28,657 --> 00:10:31,110
- I ain't seen you since the cotton farm.

207
00:10:31,110 --> 00:10:33,363
- Excuse me?
- Back in Alabama.

208
00:10:34,257 --> 00:10:35,090
(Gina stammers)

209
00:10:35,090 --> 00:10:36,583
You do remember, don't you?

210
00:10:37,990 --> 00:10:39,523
Oh, Field Pea,

211
00:10:40,680 --> 00:10:42,203
did they hit you too?

212
00:10:43,080 --> 00:10:45,600
- Ma'am, I think you
have the wrong person.

213
00:10:45,600 --> 00:10:47,730
- You're confusing my
daughter with someone else?

214
00:10:47,730 --> 00:10:49,120
- Don't be silly.

215
00:10:49,120 --> 00:10:52,490
I's knowed Field Pea since
she was knee high to a dog.

216
00:10:52,490 --> 00:10:54,360
- I'm sorry, I didn't quite get your name.

217
00:10:54,360 --> 00:10:56,970
- My name's Lilly, Lilly Cooper.

218
00:10:56,970 --> 00:10:59,583
Any friend of Field Pea's
is a friend of mine.

219
00:11:00,703 --> 00:11:02,910
- Sarah Weatherby this is my sister Wanda.

220
00:11:02,910 --> 00:11:04,230
- Howdy do.
- Hi.

221
00:11:04,230 --> 00:11:05,463
- This is our property.

222
00:11:06,768 --> 00:11:08,630
- I beg your pardon.

223
00:11:08,630 --> 00:11:10,120
- Well, our mother's.

224
00:11:10,120 --> 00:11:11,420
- Mrs. Cooper, by any chance,

225
00:11:11,420 --> 00:11:13,914
did you know our mama Mrs. Barnsdow?

226
00:11:13,914 --> 00:11:15,360
- Emma?
- Yes.

227
00:11:15,360 --> 00:11:16,203
- Emma Barnsdow?

228
00:11:17,442 --> 00:11:18,540
Sure I know her.

229
00:11:18,540 --> 00:11:21,160
She about road up to Orangeburg.

230
00:11:21,160 --> 00:11:23,410
Stock up on some dry goods for the winter.

231
00:11:23,410 --> 00:11:25,300
Gone be a cold one, you know.

232
00:11:25,300 --> 00:11:26,480
- She let you live here?

233
00:11:26,480 --> 00:11:27,857
- Of course she do.

234
00:11:27,857 --> 00:11:30,370
If she ain't back in a few weeks,

235
00:11:30,370 --> 00:11:31,870
I'm gone be mess in a of hot water

236
00:11:31,870 --> 00:11:34,700
trying to get this crop
in before the freeze.

237
00:11:34,700 --> 00:11:35,870
But why?

238
00:11:35,870 --> 00:11:37,067
Who's asking?

239
00:11:37,067 --> 00:11:38,260
- We was just wondering.

240
00:11:38,260 --> 00:11:40,210
- Well, wonder on your own time.

241
00:11:40,210 --> 00:11:42,076
I got a family to feed.

242
00:11:42,076 --> 00:11:43,640
William.

243
00:11:43,640 --> 00:11:44,527
Jenny.

244
00:11:44,527 --> 00:11:45,530
(cats mewing)

245
00:11:45,530 --> 00:11:49,349
Lulu Bell, y'all come on now
because it's supper time.

246
00:11:49,349 --> 00:11:51,429
(birds chirping)

247
00:11:51,429 --> 00:11:54,179
(camera rolling)

248
00:12:00,323 --> 00:12:03,270
- I can't believe she's
been living out there.

249
00:12:03,270 --> 00:12:04,790
- That's not right.

250
00:12:04,790 --> 00:12:05,740
It's our place now.

251
00:12:07,080 --> 00:12:09,030
- But mama let her live there.

252
00:12:09,030 --> 00:12:11,560
You know she was always
helping people like that.

253
00:12:11,560 --> 00:12:14,647
- That doesn't mean we have
to be responsible for her.

254
00:12:14,647 --> 00:12:17,920
A woman like that living by
herself she could get hurt.

255
00:12:17,920 --> 00:12:20,170
She's a liability, Wanda.

256
00:12:20,170 --> 00:12:22,670
Besides there'd been property
taxes and maintenance costs.

257
00:12:22,670 --> 00:12:24,290
We can't keep that place up.

258
00:12:24,290 --> 00:12:25,640
- So what are you gonna do?

259
00:12:27,558 --> 00:12:28,808
- I don't know.

260
00:12:30,781 --> 00:12:32,698
We can decide tomorrow.

261
00:12:40,610 --> 00:12:42,313
- [Jimmy] I can remember when
you and your little sister

262
00:12:42,313 --> 00:12:45,710
were playing in the mud out
behind Watson's Hog Farm.

263
00:12:45,710 --> 00:12:46,800
You used to pull her down there--

264
00:12:46,800 --> 00:12:48,190
- [Sarah] Jimmy, I'm sorry to say,

265
00:12:48,190 --> 00:12:50,290
I have not been doing much of that lately.

266
00:12:51,148 --> 00:12:53,813
Based on the price of some of
the other tracks out there,

267
00:12:53,813 --> 00:12:57,690
I'm guessing the place
will go for about 150,000,

268
00:12:57,690 --> 00:12:59,830
if we don't parcel, is that correct?

269
00:12:59,830 --> 00:13:02,240
- Yes, well, but I can't guarantee

270
00:13:02,240 --> 00:13:04,330
the prices will hold up now. (laughs)

271
00:13:04,330 --> 00:13:05,987
- Well, then we'll have
to move quickly, won't we?

272
00:13:05,987 --> 00:13:08,670
I'd like to put it on the
market as soon as possible.

273
00:13:08,670 --> 00:13:10,720
- Yes, but you understand,

274
00:13:10,720 --> 00:13:13,060
I have to have Wanda's consent.

275
00:13:13,060 --> 00:13:15,110
I can't--
- You'll have Wanda's consent.

276
00:13:16,020 --> 00:13:17,890
I just didn't wanna go
sticking any legal documents

277
00:13:17,890 --> 00:13:19,370
in her face right now.

278
00:13:19,370 --> 00:13:21,840
It's a very bad time, you understand.

279
00:13:21,840 --> 00:13:23,970
- Okay, yeah, sure.

280
00:13:23,970 --> 00:13:25,013
- All right, well, let me know

281
00:13:25,013 --> 00:13:26,270
the minute you have any interests.

282
00:13:26,270 --> 00:13:28,500
I'd like to have this wrapped
up by the end of the week.

283
00:13:28,500 --> 00:13:29,710
- This week yes.

284
00:13:29,710 --> 00:13:30,919
This week.

285
00:13:30,919 --> 00:13:31,919
Yes, thanks.

286
00:13:33,362 --> 00:13:34,474
This week.

287
00:13:34,474 --> 00:13:37,057
(gentle music)

288
00:13:39,160 --> 00:13:41,910
(birds chirping)

289
00:13:43,120 --> 00:13:46,203
(insects chittering)

290
00:14:24,370 --> 00:14:25,203
- Hello.

291
00:14:31,138 --> 00:14:32,721
Hello anybody home?

292
00:14:37,820 --> 00:14:39,623
Hello anyone?

293
00:14:46,900 --> 00:14:48,737
It's Field Pea.

294
00:14:48,737 --> 00:14:51,237
(cats mewing)

295
00:15:08,233 --> 00:15:11,110
- Field Pea, you done missed your train.

296
00:15:11,110 --> 00:15:13,283
- Huh?
- It left about a hour ago.

297
00:15:14,580 --> 00:15:16,440
- So you really live out here?

298
00:15:16,440 --> 00:15:18,253
- Course, I do, me and my family.

299
00:15:19,266 --> 00:15:20,270
- You know that was really cool

300
00:15:20,270 --> 00:15:22,130
how you shot that gun yesterday.

301
00:15:22,130 --> 00:15:23,983
You scared my mom to death.

302
00:15:25,300 --> 00:15:27,150
Oh, not that I wanted you to scare her.

303
00:15:27,150 --> 00:15:30,153
It's just cool how you got
her attention that's all.

304
00:15:31,251 --> 00:15:32,084
- Mm.

305
00:15:32,084 --> 00:15:34,584
(cats mewing)

306
00:15:35,507 --> 00:15:37,730
What you got there, Field Pea?

307
00:15:37,730 --> 00:15:38,610
You taking pictures?

308
00:15:38,610 --> 00:15:39,670
- Making a movie.

309
00:15:39,670 --> 00:15:42,050
- You always was interested in pictures.

310
00:15:42,050 --> 00:15:42,883
- I was.

311
00:15:44,110 --> 00:15:45,886
You wanna be a movie star, Ms. Copper?

312
00:15:45,886 --> 00:15:48,295
- Oh, shh, what I need that for?

313
00:15:48,295 --> 00:15:49,596
- Well, you'll be famous.

314
00:15:49,596 --> 00:15:51,179
Get rich and stuff.

315
00:15:53,190 --> 00:15:55,250
- I had a lot of money once.

316
00:15:55,250 --> 00:15:57,701
More than I knew what to do with.

317
00:15:57,701 --> 00:15:58,865
- Really?

318
00:15:58,865 --> 00:16:00,190
How'd you get it?

319
00:16:00,190 --> 00:16:01,513
- You remember, silly.

320
00:16:02,440 --> 00:16:06,160
It all started that
night that Skinny Babcock

321
00:16:06,160 --> 00:16:10,941
turned that old barn over by
Stony Creek into a dance hall.

322
00:16:10,941 --> 00:16:13,780
(Lilly chuckles)

323
00:16:13,780 --> 00:16:16,870
You came all the way
over to Ms. Handleman's

324
00:16:16,870 --> 00:16:19,530
just to help make me up pretty.

325
00:16:19,530 --> 00:16:20,560
Course, everybody was saying

326
00:16:20,560 --> 00:16:22,930
how funny it was that you was my friend.

327
00:16:22,930 --> 00:16:25,200
But you didn't pay them no mind.

328
00:16:25,200 --> 00:16:26,687
You said, "Best friends don't look

329
00:16:26,687 --> 00:16:28,587
"at each other for what's on the outside.

330
00:16:28,587 --> 00:16:31,440
"It's what's on the inside that counts."

331
00:16:31,440 --> 00:16:33,770
So when I decided to get me a husband,

332
00:16:33,770 --> 00:16:35,360
you wanted to help me.

333
00:16:35,360 --> 00:16:39,140
- Now remember act like you
wanna have lots of babies.

334
00:16:39,140 --> 00:16:40,080
Farmers like that.

335
00:16:40,080 --> 00:16:41,853
- I don't want a farmer, Field Pea.

336
00:16:42,890 --> 00:16:44,577
Farmers smell funny.

337
00:16:44,577 --> 00:16:46,633
- (laughs) Don't be silly,

338
00:16:46,633 --> 00:16:48,740
and don't be too pushy neither.

339
00:16:48,740 --> 00:16:52,027
Men don't like a woman
with a mind of her own.

340
00:16:52,027 --> 00:16:54,273
You just let them do all the talking,

341
00:16:55,180 --> 00:16:58,263
for a while anyway. (giggles)

342
00:16:59,130 --> 00:17:01,647
(lively music plays in hall)

343
00:17:01,647 --> 00:17:05,134
(people chattering loudly)

344
00:17:05,134 --> 00:17:07,634
(engine revs)

345
00:17:11,050 --> 00:17:12,648
- All right, y'all.

346
00:17:12,648 --> 00:17:15,648
(people chattering)

347
00:17:29,530 --> 00:17:30,980
- [Lilly] You told me don't be shy.

348
00:17:30,980 --> 00:17:34,387
You said, "Find me a good
one and just go and get him.

349
00:17:34,387 --> 00:17:37,047
"Because if I didn't,
somebody else would."

350
00:17:37,047 --> 00:17:40,630
(lively dance music plays)

351
00:17:58,694 --> 00:17:59,901
- Excuse me, Miss.

352
00:17:59,901 --> 00:18:01,068
Care to dance?

353
00:18:12,289 --> 00:18:14,314
- Hey, hey, now.

354
00:18:14,314 --> 00:18:15,652
Stay on over here, Henry.

355
00:18:15,652 --> 00:18:18,340
(soft jazzy music)

356
00:18:18,340 --> 00:18:19,669
Now, yeah.

357
00:18:19,669 --> 00:18:21,002
You coming over?

358
00:18:37,470 --> 00:18:38,363
- Well, young lady
either you came over here

359
00:18:38,363 --> 00:18:40,000
to ask me for a cigarette,

360
00:18:40,000 --> 00:18:42,253
or you'd like to dance.

361
00:18:44,980 --> 00:18:46,402
Which is it?

362
00:18:46,402 --> 00:18:49,319
(soft jazzy music)

363
00:19:29,914 --> 00:19:31,780
- And my mama she worked
on her daddy's farm.

364
00:19:31,780 --> 00:19:34,680
That's how Field Pea and
me came to be friends.

365
00:19:34,680 --> 00:19:36,059
She did my hair for me, see?

366
00:19:36,059 --> 00:19:37,380
(horn honks on street)

367
00:19:37,380 --> 00:19:40,649
- Darling, be careful this
is the only truck I got.

368
00:19:40,649 --> 00:19:42,560
But that still doesn't
explain how a nice young lady

369
00:19:42,560 --> 00:19:44,810
like yourself learned
to drive an automobile.

370
00:19:45,660 --> 00:19:47,320
- After mama died, I got a job driving

371
00:19:47,320 --> 00:19:48,680
cotton trucks to support myself.

372
00:19:48,680 --> 00:19:51,210
- Mm, you a truck driver, huh?

373
00:19:52,230 --> 00:19:55,163
Well, a skill like that could
come in handy I suppose.

374
00:19:56,220 --> 00:19:58,070
I tell you what, pull on
up to the house yonder,

375
00:19:58,070 --> 00:20:00,520
we'll stretch our legs a
little bit what you say?

376
00:20:02,410 --> 00:20:05,333
Well, now, how do you like my house?

377
00:20:06,272 --> 00:20:09,623
- Oh, Mr. Cooper, it's beautiful.

378
00:20:10,870 --> 00:20:12,420
Where'd you get all your money?

379
00:20:13,801 --> 00:20:16,433
- Well, I'm a businessman, young lady.

380
00:20:18,650 --> 00:20:19,933
So how about a toast?

381
00:20:22,080 --> 00:20:24,294
To the most beautiful lady at the dance.

382
00:20:24,294 --> 00:20:25,440
(insects chirping)

383
00:20:25,440 --> 00:20:28,190
(frogs croaking)

384
00:20:32,500 --> 00:20:33,340
- So did you marry him?

385
00:20:33,340 --> 00:20:35,040
Was that how you got the cotton farm?

386
00:20:35,040 --> 00:20:39,163
- Well, Mr. Cooper was a little
older than I had hoped for,

387
00:20:40,240 --> 00:20:42,490
but he had his charm.

388
00:20:42,490 --> 00:20:44,930
- Wow, what a way to meet a guy.

389
00:20:44,930 --> 00:20:46,570
I met Ray at the mall.

390
00:20:46,570 --> 00:20:48,490
He works at a juice bar.

391
00:20:48,490 --> 00:20:49,540
But don't tell mom that.

392
00:20:49,540 --> 00:20:51,260
She doesn't know about him yet.

393
00:20:51,260 --> 00:20:52,680
- No, no, no.

394
00:20:52,680 --> 00:20:54,410
You know, I almost forget.

395
00:20:54,410 --> 00:20:56,600
I been saving something for you.

396
00:20:56,600 --> 00:20:57,850
- [Gina] You have?

397
00:20:57,850 --> 00:20:58,683
- Yep.

398
00:20:59,571 --> 00:21:03,071
(birds chirping outside)

399
00:21:04,916 --> 00:21:07,499
(gentle music)

400
00:21:10,723 --> 00:21:12,219
- Oh, god.

401
00:21:12,219 --> 00:21:13,833
(dramatic music)

402
00:21:13,833 --> 00:21:14,666
Jerry.

403
00:21:23,090 --> 00:21:25,590
(engine revs)

404
00:21:34,036 --> 00:21:36,020
(birds chirping)

405
00:21:36,020 --> 00:21:37,319
- Hey, Aunt Wanda.
- Hey, Gina.

406
00:21:37,319 --> 00:21:39,080
- Look what she gave me.

407
00:21:39,080 --> 00:21:40,020
I saw that lady again,

408
00:21:40,020 --> 00:21:41,230
and she said that this is the necklace

409
00:21:41,230 --> 00:21:42,710
that we bought together at Woolworths

410
00:21:42,710 --> 00:21:44,350
before she went to this big dance.

411
00:21:44,350 --> 00:21:45,270
- Wait, wait, wait, wait.

412
00:21:45,270 --> 00:21:47,990
You went all the way
out there by yourself.

413
00:21:47,990 --> 00:21:49,270
- Yeah, don't tell mom.

414
00:21:49,270 --> 00:21:50,550
- Gina.

415
00:21:50,550 --> 00:21:52,200
- She kept on calling me Field Pea,

416
00:21:52,200 --> 00:21:53,830
and telling me about this guy that she met

417
00:21:53,830 --> 00:21:55,920
and used to live with on this cotton farm

418
00:21:55,920 --> 00:21:57,600
like a jillion years ago.

419
00:21:57,600 --> 00:21:58,590
- Now, Gina, wait a minute.

420
00:21:58,590 --> 00:22:01,010
You think that's a good
idea to go out there again?

421
00:22:01,010 --> 00:22:02,740
- Oh, yeah, she's cool.

422
00:22:02,740 --> 00:22:04,290
She gave me some money to buy her

423
00:22:04,290 --> 00:22:06,670
some stuff like soup and stamps.

424
00:22:06,670 --> 00:22:07,900
- Postage stamps?

425
00:22:07,900 --> 00:22:11,020
- Yeah, it's like I'm some
long-lost friend or something.

426
00:22:11,020 --> 00:22:12,560
It's really weird.

427
00:22:12,560 --> 00:22:14,170
- Wanda, I'm glad to see you.

428
00:22:14,170 --> 00:22:15,460
I got to talk to you about the property.

429
00:22:15,460 --> 00:22:16,990
Hi, darling.

430
00:22:16,990 --> 00:22:18,130
I talked to Jimmy White.

431
00:22:18,130 --> 00:22:20,560
He said if we move quickly,

432
00:22:20,560 --> 00:22:23,262
we could maybe get about a 150 for it.

433
00:22:23,262 --> 00:22:24,095
We'll split that of course.

434
00:22:24,095 --> 00:22:26,080
So that's 75 a piece.

435
00:22:26,080 --> 00:22:28,897
So I gave him the go
ahead to find a buyer.

436
00:22:28,897 --> 00:22:31,290
- $75,000.

437
00:22:31,290 --> 00:22:32,430
- Pretty nice, huh?

438
00:22:33,360 --> 00:22:36,473
- Well, yeah, if I decide to sell.

439
00:22:38,000 --> 00:22:38,920
- What do you mean?

440
00:22:38,920 --> 00:22:39,770
Why wouldn't you?

441
00:22:40,950 --> 00:22:42,210
- I don't know.

442
00:22:42,210 --> 00:22:43,907
What if I like it?

443
00:22:43,907 --> 00:22:45,920
- [Sarah] Wanda, this is not a joke.

444
00:22:45,920 --> 00:22:46,973
We stand to make a lot of money here.

445
00:22:46,973 --> 00:22:48,660
- What about Mrs. Cooper?

446
00:22:48,660 --> 00:22:50,350
- She shouldn't be out there anyway.

447
00:22:50,350 --> 00:22:52,460
I was hoping to get this
wrapped up by end of the week.

448
00:22:52,460 --> 00:22:54,140
- So you can get back
to Atlanta is that it.

449
00:22:54,140 --> 00:22:56,660
You can't stand being here one more day.

450
00:22:56,660 --> 00:22:57,880
You know it's a big decision.

451
00:22:57,880 --> 00:22:59,240
An extra day or two to think about it

452
00:22:59,240 --> 00:23:00,540
isn't gonna hurt anything.

453
00:23:03,930 --> 00:23:06,060
So how long you been
living here, Mrs. Cooper?

454
00:23:06,060 --> 00:23:08,650
- Well, since that old pecan tree fell.

455
00:23:08,650 --> 00:23:10,600
- Oh, I see.

456
00:23:10,600 --> 00:23:11,680
Have you ever thought about

457
00:23:11,680 --> 00:23:13,630
moving someplace a little bigger?

458
00:23:13,630 --> 00:23:15,640
You know, I'm sure the church
could help you find something.

459
00:23:15,640 --> 00:23:17,490
- [Lilly] Oh, no I got a family here.

460
00:23:17,490 --> 00:23:18,973
Ain't that right, Jasper?

461
00:23:19,819 --> 00:23:21,560
(cats mewing)

462
00:23:21,560 --> 00:23:23,270
- [Wanda] How often did you see my mama?

463
00:23:23,270 --> 00:23:24,103
- Who?

464
00:23:24,103 --> 00:23:26,470
- Mrs. Barnsdow from the church.

465
00:23:26,470 --> 00:23:27,840
- Emma?
- Mm-mm.

466
00:23:27,840 --> 00:23:28,800
- All the time.

467
00:23:28,800 --> 00:23:31,200
Matter of fact, she's
supposed to be here tomorrow.

468
00:23:31,200 --> 00:23:33,093
We'll be hiring for the fall soon.

469
00:23:34,560 --> 00:23:35,890
- Mrs. Cooper.
- Mm-hmm.

470
00:23:35,890 --> 00:23:36,990
- My mama, Mrs. Barnsdow.

471
00:23:36,990 --> 00:23:38,550
- Mm-hmm.

472
00:23:38,550 --> 00:23:41,430
- You know, she died last week.

473
00:23:41,430 --> 00:23:43,680
Oh, she was real sick.

474
00:23:43,680 --> 00:23:44,513
- No.

475
00:23:45,380 --> 00:23:46,693
Emma's in Orangeburg.

476
00:23:48,710 --> 00:23:50,360
That's just a rumor.

477
00:23:50,360 --> 00:23:52,210
Too much work to be done around here.

478
00:23:55,940 --> 00:23:58,410
- Why don't you tell her
about the cotton farm,

479
00:23:58,410 --> 00:24:00,130
you know, like you were telling me.

480
00:24:00,130 --> 00:24:02,770
- It was the most wonderful
place in the world.

481
00:24:02,770 --> 00:24:04,370
- Did you really have a cotton farm?

482
00:24:04,370 --> 00:24:07,150
- Yes, I did, first home I ever had.

483
00:24:07,150 --> 00:24:08,190
Being an orphan and all,

484
00:24:08,190 --> 00:24:10,580
I never had no proper
place till I met Henry.

485
00:24:10,580 --> 00:24:12,290
- Henry was her husband.

486
00:24:12,290 --> 00:24:14,470
- I was planning on having lots of babies.

487
00:24:14,470 --> 00:24:15,910
That's why when I moved in,

488
00:24:15,910 --> 00:24:18,772
I tried to make sure they'd
have a good home to grow up in.

489
00:24:18,772 --> 00:24:21,605
(dramatic music)

490
00:24:26,690 --> 00:24:28,760
But Mr. Cooper had other plans.

491
00:24:28,760 --> 00:24:32,285
With him, it was always work, work, work.

492
00:24:32,285 --> 00:24:34,355
- [Henry] Lily.

493
00:24:34,355 --> 00:24:37,105
(dramatic music)

494
00:24:53,413 --> 00:24:55,913
(engine revs)

495
00:25:05,730 --> 00:25:07,120
- [Wanda] So you were driving that truck

496
00:25:07,120 --> 00:25:09,163
for your husband's business, huh?

497
00:25:09,163 --> 00:25:12,142
- [Lilly] Mm-mm, and
sometimes for days on end.

498
00:25:12,142 --> 00:25:15,700
Why he'd have me trucking cotton
seed clear into Mississippi

499
00:25:15,700 --> 00:25:19,220
and sometimes to folks that
didn't even look like farmers.

500
00:25:19,220 --> 00:25:21,490
I didn't know who my husband
was doing business with,

501
00:25:21,490 --> 00:25:24,603
but we was doing okay, I suppose.

502
00:25:28,610 --> 00:25:31,050
- [Wanda] Mrs. Cooper it's
been a pleasure talking to you.

503
00:25:31,050 --> 00:25:32,620
- And it's been a pleasure
talking to you too.

504
00:25:32,620 --> 00:25:34,050
- Well, thank you.

505
00:25:34,050 --> 00:25:38,480
- Field Pea, don't forget to
tell Emma about the hiring.

506
00:25:38,480 --> 00:25:41,205
We gone need 12 good workers this year.

507
00:25:41,205 --> 00:25:43,133
- Okay.
- Okay.

508
00:25:43,133 --> 00:25:45,190
Oh, oh, oh, Field Pea.

509
00:25:45,190 --> 00:25:47,870
Field Pea, sit this bucket out there

510
00:25:47,870 --> 00:25:49,970
because we sure don't need no more rain

511
00:25:49,970 --> 00:25:51,313
come harvesting time.

512
00:25:53,410 --> 00:25:54,960
- But don't you see?

513
00:25:54,960 --> 00:25:56,590
It's the same thing.

514
00:25:56,590 --> 00:25:58,410
That's who mama got the
story of the bucket from.

515
00:25:58,410 --> 00:25:59,930
Mrs. Cooper told her.

516
00:25:59,930 --> 00:26:01,010
- Yeah.

517
00:26:01,010 --> 00:26:01,843
So.

518
00:26:02,877 --> 00:26:04,967
- So, it's just neat that's all.

519
00:26:06,390 --> 00:26:07,223
- Darling,

520
00:26:08,318 --> 00:26:10,153
$75,000 would be neat.

521
00:26:15,791 --> 00:26:16,775
(birds chirping)

522
00:26:16,775 --> 00:26:19,525
(engine revving)

523
00:26:21,158 --> 00:26:23,350
- And then every year at Christmas,

524
00:26:23,350 --> 00:26:26,073
daddy would give hayrides
to all the children in town.

525
00:26:27,087 --> 00:26:28,883
There're lots of memories out here.

526
00:26:29,960 --> 00:26:33,300
Oh, my goodness that must
be my daddy's old tractor.

527
00:26:33,300 --> 00:26:35,900
- I think there's real
investment potential here.

528
00:26:35,900 --> 00:26:37,100
Something special.

529
00:26:37,100 --> 00:26:39,550
Now if I was to buy this place,

530
00:26:39,550 --> 00:26:41,880
I'd think about clearing
out some of those trees

531
00:26:41,880 --> 00:26:43,570
and putting a house right there.

